# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jamstack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API provides an interface for fetching resources (including across the network).
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] It is a more powerful and flexible replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API uses `Request` and `Response` objects (and other things involved with network requests), as well as related concepts such as CORS and the HTTP Origin header semantics.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] For making a request and fetching a resource, use the `fetch()` method.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] It is a global method in both `Window` and `Worker` contexts.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] This makes it available in pretty much any context you might want to fetch resources in.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method takes one mandatory argument, the path to the resource you want to fetch.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] It returns a `Promise` that resolves to the `Response` to that request — as soon as the server responds with headers — **even if the server response is an HTTP error status**.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] You can also optionally pass in an `init` options object as the second argument (see `Request`).
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] Once a `Response` is retrieved, there are a number of methods available to define what the body content is and how it should be handled.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] You can create a request and response directly using the `Request()` and `Response()` constructors, but it's uncommon to do this directly.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] Instead, these are more likely to be created as results of other API actions (for example, `FetchEvent.respondWith()` from service workers).
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] Find out more about using the Fetch API features in Using Fetch.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] The `fetchLater()` API enables a developer to request a *deferred fetch*, that can be sent after a specified period of time, or when the page is closed or navigated away from.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method used to fetch a resource.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] Represents the set of options that can be used to configure a deferred fetch request.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] Represents the result of requesting a deferred fetch.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] Represents response/request headers, allowing you to query them and take different actions depending on the results.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] Controls the top-level quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:jamstack/api-fetch-api] Controls the shared cross-origin subframe quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The Fetch API provides a JavaScript interface for making HTTP requests and processing the responses.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Fetch is the modern replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`: unlike `XMLHttpRequest`, which uses callbacks, Fetch is promise-based and is integrated with features of the modern web such as service workers and Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS).
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] With the Fetch API, you make a request by calling `fetch()`, which is available as a global function in both `window` and `worker` contexts.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] You pass it a `Request` object or a string containing the URL to fetch, along with an optional argument to configure the request.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled with a `Response` object representing the server's response.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] You can then check the request status and extract the body of the response in various formats, including text and JSON, by calling the appropriate method on the response.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] We declare a string containing the URL and then call `fetch()`, passing the URL with no extra options.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function will reject the promise on some errors, but not if the server responds with an error status like `404`: so we also check the response status and throw if it is not OK.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Otherwise, we fetch the response body content as JSON by calling the `json()` method of `Response`, and log one of its values.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that like `fetch()` itself, `json()` is asynchronous, as are all the other methods to access the response body content.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the rest of this page we'll look in more detail at the different stages of this process.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] 2. optionally, an object containing options to configure the request.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this section we'll look at some of the most commonly-used options.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] To read about all the options that can be given, see the `fetch()` reference page.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then `method` must be one of `GET`, `POST` or `HEAD`.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The request body is the payload of the request: it's the thing the client is sending to the server.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] You cannot include a body with `GET` requests, but it's useful for requests that send content to the server, such as `POST` or `PUT` requests.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, if you want to upload a file to the server, you might make a `POST` request and include the file as the request body.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Other objects are converted to strings using their `toString()` method.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] See Locked and disturbed streams for more information.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request headers give the server information about the request: for example, in a `POST` request, the `Content-Type` header tells the server the format of the request's body.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] To set request headers, assign them to the `headers` option.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Compared to using plain objects, the `Headers` object provides some additional input sanitization.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, it normalizes header names to lowercase, strips leading and trailing whitespace from header values, and prevents certain headers from being set.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Many headers are set automatically by the browser and can't be set by a script: these are called Forbidden request headers.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then the set of permitted headers is further restricted.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] `GET` requests don't have a body, but you can still send data to the server by appending it to the URL as a query string.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common way to send form data to the server.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Whether a request can be made cross-origin or not is determined by the value of the `RequestInit.mode` option.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] This may take one of three values: `cors`, `same-origin`, or `no-cors`.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] See the reference documentation for `RequestInit.mode` for more details.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the context of the Fetch API, a credential is an extra piece of data sent along with the request that the server may use to authenticate the user.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] By default, credentials are only included in same-origin requests.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that if a cookie's `SameSite` attribute is set to `Strict` or `Lax`, then the cookie will not be sent cross-site, even if `credentials` is set to `include`.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Including credentials in cross-origin requests can make a site vulnerable to CSRF attacks, so even if `credentials` is set to `include`, the server must also agree to their inclusion by including the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header in its response.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Additionally, in this situation the server must explicitly specify the client's origin in the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header (that is, `*` is not allowed).
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Request()` constructor takes the same arguments as `fetch()` itself.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] This means that instead of passing options into `fetch()`, you can pass the same options to the `Request()` constructor, and then pass that object to `fetch()`.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] To make a request cancelable, create an `AbortController`, and assign its `AbortSignal` to the request's `signal` property.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] To cancel the request, call the controller's `abort()` method.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` call will reject the promise with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the request is aborted after the `fetch()` call has been fulfilled but before the response body has been read, then attempting to read the response body will reject with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] As soon as the browser has received the response status and headers from the server (and potentially before the response body itself has been received), the promise returned by `fetch()` is fulfilled with a `Response` object.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The promise returned by `fetch()` will reject on some errors, such as a network error or a bad scheme.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] However, if the server responds with an error like `404`, then `fetch()` fulfills with a `Response`, so we have to check the status before we can read the response body.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Response.status` property tells us the numerical status code, and the `Response.ok` property returns `true` if the status is in the 200 range.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Just like the request, the response has a `headers` property which is a `Headers` object, and this contains any response headers that are exposed to scripts, subject to the exclusions made based on the response type.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] These are all asynchronous methods, returning a `Promise` which will be fulfilled with the body content.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The method will throw an exception if the response body is not in the appropriate format: for example, if you call `json()` on a response that can't be parsed as JSON.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request and response bodies are actually `ReadableStream` objects, and whenever you read them, you're streaming the content.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is good for memory efficiency, because the browser doesn't have to buffer the entire response in memory before the caller retrieves it using a method like `json()`.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] This also means that the caller can process the content incrementally as it is received.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] If we use `Response.text()`, as above, we must wait until the whole file has been received before we can process any of it.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this example, we iterate asynchronously over the stream, processing each chunk as it arrives.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that when you access the body directly like this, you get the raw bytes of the response and must transform it yourself.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this case we call `ReadableStream.pipeThrough()` to pipe the response through a `TextDecoderStream`, which decodes the UTF-8-encoded body data as text.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the example below, we fetch a text resource and process it line by line, using a regular expression to look for line endings.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common pattern when implementing an offline cache with service workers.
[src:jamstack/fetch-api-using-fetch] The service worker wants to return the response to the app, but also to cache the response.
[src:jamstack/glossary-ssg] A **static site generator** (SSG) is a software used to generate *static* websites.
[src:jamstack/glossary-ssg] A static website is comprised of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files.
[src:jamstack/glossary-ssg] Most importantly static sites do not have server-side logic, so for any given URL, all users will receive the same content.
[src:jamstack/glossary-ssg] Authors write content in any form accepted by the generator, such as Markdown, reStructuredText, HTML, (and sometimes even React, and so on), and the generator compiles them into a set of optimized static files that can be rendered by the browser.
[src:jamstack/glossary-ssg] Static sites are commonly used for blogs, documentation, and other content-driven websites, which don't have data that needs to be fetched or generated server-side.
[src:jamstack/glossary-ssg] They are fast, secure, and easier to deploy, because they can be served from a CDN.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] SSGs typically consist of a template written in HTML with a templating system, such as Liquid (Jekyll) or Go template (Hugo).
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] The same structure (typically a Git repository) includes content in a plain-text format such as Markdown or reStructuredText, or in a structural meta format such as JSON or XML.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] A single plain-text file may correspond to a single web page.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] Alternatively, a single structural metadata file may correspond to an entire website if a single-page application framework like AngularJS is used.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] The website variable settings are stored in a plaintext configuration file `_config.yml` (YAML), `_config.toml` (TOML) or `_config.json` (JSON).
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] Page files typically also start with a YAML, TOML, or JSON preamble to define variables such as title, permalink, or date.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] Files with names that begin with an underscore (`_`) such as `_index.md` (as opposed to `index.md`) are considered templates or archetypes and are thus not rendered as pages themselves.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] Several hundred SSGs have been documented to exist, with the vast majority being written in languages that are already prominent on the web, such as Python, Go, JavaScript and TypeScript.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] Many *server-side template systems* have the option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existing software adapted for this task.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for web use, running on CGI.
[src:jamstack/static-site-generator] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, starting with SSI.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Since the World Wide Web was released publicly in 1993, web development has evolved greatly, with websites changing from a collection of static HTML pages to complex projects using frameworks, servers, and databases.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Web development includes many individual tasks, including web design, web content development, networking, and coding.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Among web professionals, "web development" usually refers to the main non-design aspects of building websites: writing markup and coding.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Web development is generally split into two fields: front-end development and back-end development.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Front-end developers create the user interface of websites, turning web designs into HTML, CSS, and JavaScript code.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Front-end developers must also make sure that websites work consistently across different browsers and devices.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Back-end development, also known as server-side development, focuses on the infrastructure behind a website, including APIs, database management, and security.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Some choose to be full-stack developers, meaning they work on both the front-end and back-end.
[src:jamstack/web-development] The World Wide Web is often categorised into three generations: Web 1.0, Web 2.0, and Web 3.0 (or Web3).
[src:jamstack/web-development] It was invented in 1989, and released to the public in 1993.
[src:jamstack/web-development] In the early years of the web, restrospecitvely referred to as Web 1.0, websites were simply a collection of static HTML files, and had limited interactivity.
[src:jamstack/web-development] After the introduction of JavaScript in 1995, websites could contain logic, allowing for interactivity.
[src:jamstack/web-development] The following year CSS was released, allowing greater control over the styling of web pages.
[src:jamstack/web-development] In 1999, the term *Web 2.0* was coined by Darcy DiNucci.
[src:jamstack/web-development] The term later resurfaced in the early 2000s, as websites started to increase in complexity, requiring server-side services in addition to JavaScript.
[src:jamstack/web-development] This led to the emergence of various new programming languages and frameworks designed for backend services, such as PHP, Active Server Pages, and Jakarta Server Pages.
[src:jamstack/web-development] This enabled websites to do additional server-side processing, such as accessing databases.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Another shift in web development was the release of the iPhone in 2007.
[src:jamstack/web-development] This created a new medium for accessing the web, requiring a new approach to web development, and resulting in responsive web design, which allows a single website to appear different depending on the device running it.
[src:jamstack/web-development] Later, progressive web apps were introduced, allowing websites to be installed on a device as an independent application.
[src:jamstack/web-development] In the 2010s, JavaScript frameworks began to emerge, creating new ways to manipulate web pages, and increasing compatibility between web browsers.
[src:jamstack/web-development] JQuery was popular in the early 2010s, but was later surpassed by other frameworks such as React and Vue.js.
[src:jamstack/web-development] In the mid 2020s, use of AI became prevalent among web developers, with the 2025 Stack Overflow survey showing over 80% of developers saying the use AI at least monthly in their development process.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:jamstack/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:jamstack/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:jamstack/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:jamstack/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:jamstack/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:jamstack/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:jamstack/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:jamstack/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
